{{Campaignbox Croatian War of Independence}}
The '''Battle of Osijek''' ({{lang-hr|Bitka za Osijek}}) was the artillery bombardment of the [[Croatia]]n city of [[Osijek]] by the [[Yugoslav People's Army]] (JNA) which took place from August 1991 to June 1992 during the [[Croatian War of Independence]]. Shelling peaked in late November and December 1991, then diminished in 1992 after the [[Vance plan]] was accepted by the combatants. [[Airstrike]]s and attacks by JNA infantry and armored units against targets in the city accompanied the bombardment, which caused approximately 800 deaths and resulted in a large portion of the city's population leaving. Croatian sources estimated that 6,000 artillery shells were fired against Osijek over the period.

After the JNA [[Battle of Vukovar|captured Vukovar]] on 18 November 1991, Osijek was the next target for its [[1991 Yugoslav campaign in Croatia|campaign in Croatia]]. The JNA units subordinated to the 12th ([[Novi Sad]]) Corps, supported by the [[Serb Volunteer Guard]], achieved modest advances in late November and early December, capturing several villages south of Osijek, but the [[Croatian Army]] maintained its defensive front and limited the JNA's advances.

In the aftermath of the Battle of Osijek, Croatian authorities charged thirteen JNA officers with [[war crime]]s against civilians, but no arrests have been made to date. Croatian authorities also charged the wartime commander of Osijek's defence, [[Branimir Glavaš]], and five others with war crimes committed in the city in 1991. The five were convicted and received sentences ranging between eight and ten years, and as of March 2015, judicial proceedings against Glavaš are in progress.

==Background==
In 1990, following the [[Croatian parliamentary election, 1990|electoral defeat]] of the government of the [[Socialist Republic of Croatia]], ethnic tensions worsened. The [[Yugoslav People's Army]] (''Jugoslovenska Narodna Armija'' – JNA) confiscated the weapons of Croatia's [[Territorial Defense Forces (Yugoslavia)|Territorial Defence]] (''Teritorijalna obrana'' – TO) to minimize potential resistance.{{sfn|Hoare|2010|p=117}} On 17 August 1990, the escalating tensions turned into [[Log Revolution|open revolt]] by the [[Serbs of Croatia|Croatian Serbs]].{{sfn|Hoare|2010|p=118}} The revolt took place in the predominantly Serb-populated areas of the [[Dalmatia]]n hinterland around [[Knin]]{{sfn|The New York Times|19 August 1990}} and in parts of the [[Lika]], [[Kordun]], [[Banovina (region)|Banovina]] regions and [[eastern Croatia]].{{sfn|Woodward|1995|p=170}} In January 1991, [[Republic of Serbia (1990–2006)|Serbia]], supported by [[Socialist Republic of Montenegro|Montenegro]] and Serbia's provinces of [[Vojvodina]] and [[Autonomous Province of Kosovo and Metohija|Kosovo]], made two unsuccessful attempts to obtain approval from the [[Yugoslav Presidency]] to deploy the JNA to disarm Croatian security forces.{{sfn|Hoare|2010|pp=118–119}}

After [[Pakrac clash|a bloodless skirmish]] between Serb insurgents and [[Croatian special police order of battle in 1991–95|Croatian special police]] in March,{{sfn|Ramet|2006|pp=384–385}} the JNA itself, supported by Serbia and its allies, asked the federal Presidency to grant it wartime powers and declare a [[state of emergency]]. The request was denied on 15 March 1991,{{sfn|Hoare|2010|p=119}} and the JNA came under the control of Serbian President [[Slobodan Milošević]] in the summer of 1991 as the Yugoslav federation started to fall apart.{{sfn|Sell|2002|p=373}} By the end of the month, the conflict had escalated, resulting in the [[Plitvice Lakes incident|first fatalities]] of the war.{{sfn|The New York Times|3 March 1991}} The JNA then stepped in to support the insurgents and prevent [[Law enforcement in Croatia|Croatian police]] from intervening.{{sfn|Hoare|2010|p=119}} In early April, leaders of the Serb revolt in Croatia announced their intention to integrate the areas under their control with Serbia. The [[Government of Croatia]] considered this an act of [[secession]].{{sfn|The New York Times|2 April 1991}}

==Timeline==
[[File:Map 3 - Croatia - Eastern Slavonia - September 1991 - January 1992.jpg|thumb|300px|Map showing the fighting in eastern Slavonia, September 1991 – January 1992; Osijek is located in the bulge (salient) near the top of the map]]
The JNA intervened directly against Croatia for the first time on 3 July 1991, driving Croatian forces out of [[Baranja]], north of the city of [[Osijek]],{{sfn|Ramet|2006|p=397}} and out of [[Erdut]], [[Aljmaš, Croatia|Aljmaš]] and [[Dalj]] east of Osijek.{{sfn|Marijan|2012a|p=111}} The advance was followed by intermittent fighting around Osijek, [[Vukovar]] and [[Vinkovci]].{{sfn|CIA|2002|p=93}} At several points, JNA positions approached to within several hundred yards of Osijek city limits.{{sfn|The Washington Post|6 September 1991}}

The JNA units near Osijek were subordinated to the 12th ([[Novi Sad]]) Corps,{{sfn|Marijan|2012b|p=261}} commanded by [[Major General]] [[Andrija Biorčević]].{{sfn|Vreme|7 September 2006}} In the city itself, the JNA had several barracks which housed the 12th Proletarian Mechanised Brigade and the 12th Mixed Artillery Regiment.{{sfn|CIA|2002b|p=103}} The 12th Proletarian Mechanised Brigade contained one of a handful battalions maintained by the JNA at full [[combat readiness]].{{sfn|Marijan|2003|loc=note 20}} Osijek was established as their starting point in a [[1991 Yugoslav campaign in Croatia|planned westward offensive]] toward [[Našice]] and [[Bjelovar]].{{sfn|Marijan|2012b|p=261}}

Croatian forces in the area were formally subordinated to the Operational Zone Command in Osijek headed by Colonel [[Karl Gorinšek]].{{sfn|Slobodna Dalmacija|8 November 2003}} In practice, the city's defense was overseen by [[Branimir Glavaš]], then head of the National Defence Office in Osijek, according to information presented at Glavaš trial in the 2000s. Glavaš formally became commander of city defenses on 7 December 1991.{{sfn|Slobodna Dalmacija|26 October 2006}}

===Bombardment of the city===
[[File:Osijek-2.JPG|thumb|left|Partially repaired bombardment damage in Osijek]]
The JNA first attacked Osijek by mortar fire on 31 July 1991,{{sfn|Libal|1997|p=30}} and heavily bombarded the city's center on 19 August 1991.{{sfn|Libal|1997|p=38}} The attacks came from positions north, east and south of Osijek,{{sfn|Ramsbotham|Miall|Woodhouse|2011|pp=308, 310}} and were supported by JNA garrisons stationed in Osijek itself.{{sfn|Mesić|2004|p=233}} On 7–9 September, an inconclusive battle was fought in [[Tenja]], within {{convert|3|km|abbr=off|spell=in}} of the city.{{sfn|CIA|2002b|p=86}} The [[Battle of the Barracks|JNA garrisons were besieged]] by Croatian forces in mid-September. After a barracks in the city centre was captured on 15 September 1991,{{sfn|Nacional|24 October 2006}} the remaining JNA garrison tried to break through the Croatian troops besieging the barracks and, after heavy fighting, reached JNA positions south of Osijek on 17 September 1991.{{sfn|CIA|2002b|p=103}} The intensity of the shelling increased thereafter, peaking through November and December. After a ceasefire was arranged in January 1992, following the acceptance of the [[Vance plan]], the artillery attacks dropped off and became intermittent,{{sfn|Jegen|1996|p=14}} and ceased by June.{{sfn|Ramsbotham|Miall|Woodhouse|2011|pp=308, 310}}

During its height, the intensity of the bombardment was reported to reach as high as one shell per minute,{{sfn|Bailey|2004|p=435}} and the artillery attacks were compounded by [[Yugoslav Air Force]] strikes against the city.{{sfn|Ramet|2006|p=409}} According to Croatian sources, a total of 6,000 artillery shells were fired against Osijek in the period.{{sfn|Nacional|27 April 2012}} Prior to the start of the bombardment, the civilian population of Osijek totaled 104,761 city residents and 129,792 municipal residents.{{sfn|Andraković|Jukić|2009|p=31}} These numbers were significantly reduced as civilians fled the fighting. It is estimated that only about a third of the population remained in the city by the end of November,{{sfn|Los Angeles Times|26 November 1991}} with some sources placing the estimate even lower, suggesting that the population of the city was reduced to just 10,000 civilians during the most intense periods of the bombardment.{{sfn|Ramsbotham|Miall|Woodhouse|2011|p=308}} Those who remained in Osijek through the fighting generally slept in [[bomb shelter]]s.{{sfn|The Washington Post|6 September 1991}}

===Ground offensive===
