After JNA [[Battle of Vukovar|captured Vukovar]] on 18 November, the JNA 12th (Novi Sad) Corps, supported by the Serbian Ministry of Interior-trained [[Serb Volunteer Guard]] paramilitaries,{{sfn|CIA|2002|pp=101–102}}{{sfn|Macdonald|2002|p=104}} started to advance west between Vinkovci and Osijek on 20 November.{{sfn|CIA|2002|pp=101–102}} The city of Osijek appeared to be the next target of the JNA,{{sfn|Ahrens|2007|p=117}} which was later confirmed by General [[Života Panić]], commander of the JNA 1st Military District.{{sfn|CIA|2002b|p=208}}

On 21 November 1991, the JNA captured the villages of Stari Seleš, Novi Seleš and [[Ernestinovo]] situated approximately {{convert|10|km|abbr=off|spell=in}} south of Osijek. [[Laslovo]], {{convert|5|km|abbr=off|spell=in}} south of Ernestinovo, was captured three days later. Those developments threatened [[Đakovo]] and pointed to the potential encirclement of Osijek.{{sfn|Marijan|2012a|p=111}} On 4 December 1991, the [[Special Envoy]] of [[Secretary-General of the United Nations]] [[Cyrus Vance]] visited Osijek to inspect the damage.{{sfn|The Washington Post|4 December 1991}}

In early December, the JNA made modest advances, capturing [[Antunovac]] located {{convert|6|km|abbr=off|spell=in}} south of Osijek on 5 December 1991.{{sfn|Marijan|2012a|p=111}} On the same day, an armoured JNA force unsuccessfully attacked positions held by the Croatian 106th Brigade in Rosinjača Forest near [[Nemetin]], approximately {{convert|2|km|abbr=off|spell=in}} east of Osijek.{{sfn|Glas Slavonije|6 December 2012}} On 6 December, the JNA pushed Croatian troops out from Tenja,{{sfn|Marijan|2012a|p=111}} followed by a heavy attack against Osijek repulsed by the [[Croatian Army]] (''Hrvatska vojska'' {{ndash}} HV) on 7 December.{{sfn|Los Angeles Times|9 December 1991}} On 11 December, HV personnel entered the frontline village of [[Paulin Dvor]], less than {{convert|3|km|abbr=off|spell=in}} kilometers west of Ernestinovo,{{sfn|Marijan|2012a|p=111}} and summarily executed 19 civilians (18 Serbs and one Hungarian).{{sfn|BBC|4 November 2010}}{{sfn|B92|11 December 2011}} The JNA captured Paulin Dvor five days later, on 16 December,{{sfn|Marijan|2012a|p=111}} and attacked Osijek once again.{{sfn|Fraser|17 December 1991}} The HV managed to contain the attack, though fighting continued south of Osijek until January 1992.{{sfn|CIA|2002|pp=101–102}}

===Operation Devil's Beam===
Advances of the JNA north of Osijek threatened HV control of a narrow [[bridgehead]] held across the [[Drava]] River skirting the city's northern edge. By mid-December the bridgehead was reduced to a strip of land opposite Osijek, encompassing suburban settlements of Podravlje and Tvrđavica. In order to remove the threat, the HV launched an offensive [[codename]]d Operation Devil's Beam ({{lang-hr|Operacija Đavolja greda|links=no}}) on 17–18 December. The offensive, involving the 1st Battalion of the 135th Brigade, elements of the [[special forces]] Frankopan Battalion and the Osijek-based [[Croatian special police order of battle in 1991–95|Orao special police unit]], Drava River flotilla, artillery of the 106th Brigade,{{sfn|SIB.hr|23 December 2013}} and personnel of the 4th [[Beli Manastir]] Police Station,{{sfn|Bajto|18 December 2011}} successfully pushed the JNA north, across Stara Drava [[oxbow lake]] located approximately {{convert|4|km|abbr=off|spell=in}} north of Osijek.{{sfn|Pejić|19 December 2014}} The JNA also withdrew from the village of [[Kopačevo]] towards [[Darda, Croatia|Darda]] and [[Vardarac]], but the HV did not have sufficient resources to exploit the development.{{sfn|Alilović|18 December 2014}} The HV lost eight killed in the offensive,{{sfn|Zelenić|18 December 2014}} but the JNA's advance towards Osijek from the north was halted.{{sfn|Bajto|18 December 2011}}

==Aftermath==
By June 1992, approximately 800 people had been killed by the bombardment.{{sfn|Jegen|1996|p=14}} By the end of the [[Croatian War of Independence]] in 1995, a total of 1,724 people from Osijek had been killed, including 1,327 soldiers and 397 civilians.{{sfn|HRT|28 June 2012}} The city itself suffered great damage during the war, with the bulk of direct damage occurring as a consequence of the 1991–92 bombardment.{{sfn|Pavičić|2009|p=150}} Direct war damage sustained by the city was estimated at a total of US$1.3&nbsp;billion.{{sfn|Pavičić|2009|p=154}} The damage was regularly recorded by 400 volunteers during the bombardment.{{sfn|Pavičić|2009|p=153}}

Although media reported on the bombardment of Osijek, journalists in the city itself felt that it was receiving an unduly low level of media coverage compared to wartime events elsewhere in Croatia.{{sfn|Mercier|1995|p=135}} The attacks on Osijek were welcomed by the ''Pravoslavlje'' newspaper published by the [[Serbian Orthodox Church]], which appeared to give a blessing to the attack as a part of a "[[holy war]]", setting it in the context of [[List of massacres in the Independent State of Croatia|World War II massacres]] and [[concentration camps in the Independent State of Croatia]].{{sfn|Ramet|2006|p=400}}

The JNA withdrew from Croatia in 1992, but continued to contribute personnel and equipment to the [[Army of the Republic of Serbian Krajina]] (ARSK) which controlled the areas previously held by the JNA.{{sfn|Armatta|2010|p=216}} Although the [[United Nations Protection Force]] peacekeepers deployed to the area on the basis of the Vance plan and placed most of the ARSK heavy weapons in storage,{{sfn|CIA|2002|p=107}} Osijek was intermittently bombarded throughout the war—the last artillery strike occurred in September 1995.{{sfn|Večernji list|16 November 2011}} The hostilities ceased in November 1995 through the [[Erdut Agreement]] securing restoration of Croatian rule in the region.{{sfn|Ramet|Matić|2007|p=46}}

In November 2010, then-Croatian President [[Ivo Josipović]] officially apologized for the [[Paulin Dvor massacre]], shortly after his Serbian counterpart [[Boris Tadić]] issued a formal apology for the [[Vukovar massacre|massacre at Vukovar]].{{sfn|BBC|4 November 2010}}

===War crime trials===
In 2008, Croatian authorities formally charged Colonel Boro Ivanović, commanding officer of the JNA 12th Proletarian Mechanised Brigade, and twelve other JNA officers with [[war crime]]s against the civilian population. The charges include causing the deaths of 307 civilians in Osijek and surrounding areas, injuries to another 171 civilians, and the destruction of at least 1,188 different structures. {{As of|2013}}, all of the indicted officers remain at large in [[Serbia]].{{sfn|Blic|17 November 2008}}

In 2005, the Osijek District Court convicted former Croatian soldier Nikola Ivanković for his involvement in the killings at Paulin Dvor, and sentenced him to 15 years in prison. In 2012, Enes Vitesković was also convicted for his involvement in the atrocity, and given an eleven-year sentence.{{sfn|B92|11 December 2011}}

After the war, five Croatian fighters were charged and convicted of eleven counts of murder, one of attempted murder, and one of torture of Serb civilians found in the JNA barracks, which surrendered on 15 September 1991. They received prison sentences of between five and eight years. Glavaš, who was tried alongside them for the same crimes, received a ten-year sentence.{{sfn|Nacional|24 October 2006}}{{sfn|Nacional|8 May 2009}} Before the conviction became final in 2009, and to avoid [[extradition]], Glavaš fled to [[Bosnia and Herzegovina]], where he had granted citizenship. His sentence was reduced to eight years and became final in 2010, when he was arrested and imprisoned in Bosnia and Herzegovina.{{sfn|Nacional|28 September 2010}} In January 2015, the conviction was set aside by the [[Constitutional Court of Croatia]], pending a new trial before the [[Supreme Court of Croatia]].{{sfn|Jurasić|12 January 2015}}

